    <text>
        <body>
            <head>General Rules</head>
            <p>As set down by <persName><ptr target="../persons/2180"/>John Wesley</persName> in <hi
                    rend="italic">The Nature, Design, and General Rules of the United Societies
                        (<date when="1743">1743</date>)</hi>, the General Rules are three simple
                categories that link together Christian doctrine and Christian living. Wesley
                expected the Methodists to embody holiness &quot;First: By doing no harm, by
                avoiding evil of every kind…. Secondly: By…doing good of every possible sort, and,
                as far as possible, to all…. Thirdly: By attending upon all the ordinances of
                God.&quot; While the first rule and second rule roughly encapsulate the first two
                principles of natural law, the third rule points to Wesley&amp;s teachings on using
                the means of grace, including prayer, searching the Scriptures, fasting, and
                Eucharist. The General Rules are still embraced by Wesleyans and Methodists
                today.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
